  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "A red chalk drawing with white heightening on paper by **Michelangelo Buonarroti** (1475–1564), c. 1511, depicting a study for one of the **ignudi** (nude male figures) on the Sistine Chapel ceiling, most probably near the Persian Sibyl / Separation of the Earth from the Waters. Described as \"probably the best-preserved example\" of Michelangelo's Sistine preparatory studies. The verso (A 027 verso) contains swift sketches of figures surrounding God the Father in the **Creation of Adam** — connecting this single sheet to two of the most significant Sistine compositions. Part of approximately 22–25 Michelangelo drawings at Teylers, forming one of the **top five collections of Michelangelo drawings in the world**, acquired in 1790 via Willem Anne Lestevenon from the Odescalchi heirs in Rome for 10,000 guilders. Designated one of Teylers' **50 Topstukken**.",
